                <h2>Introduction</h2>
                <p>This resource explores the art of persuasive speaking by connecting traditional Māori oratory (<span class="maori-term">whaikōrero</span>) with contemporary debate skills. Students will learn how the structure, techniques, and cultural protocols of <span class="maori-term">whaikōrero</span> can enhance modern debating practices.</p>
                
                <div class="interactive-element" onclick="toggleContent('cultural-context')">
                    <h3>Cultural Context: Whaikōrero</h3>
                    <p>Click to learn about the significance of whaikōrero in Māori culture</p>
                    <div id="cultural-context" style="display: none; margin-top: 15px;">
                        <p><span class="maori-term">Whaikōrero</span> (formal speech-making) is a cornerstone of Māori culture, traditionally performed by men on the <span class="maori-term">marae</span> (meeting grounds). It follows specific protocols and structures that have been refined over generations.</p>
                        <p>Key elements include:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><span class="maori-term">Tauparapara</span> - Opening incantations that acknowledge spiritual connections</li>
                            <li><span class="maori-term">Whakapapa</span> - Genealogical connections that establish speaker authority</li>
                            <li>References to landmarks and ancestors to ground the speech in place and history</li>
                            <li>Use of metaphor and poetic language (<span class="maori-term">kīwaha</span> and <span class="maori-term">whakataukī</span>)</li>
                            <li>Structured progression from past to present to future</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            

